<text top="73" left="263" width="496" height="54" font="1">Examining Email Spam</text>
<text top="157" left="246" width="884" height="34" font="2">Email Spam might seem like just a nuisance but there are costs to </text>
<text top="193" left="246" width="714" height="34" font="2">• The recipient of download (now a historical issue?)</text>
<text top="229" left="246" width="919" height="34" font="2">• The recipient in time spent dealing with the email if it gets through </text>
<text top="265" left="287" width="236" height="34" font="2">their spam filters?</text>
<text top="301" left="246" width="856" height="34" font="2">• The recipient of mis-identified emails (MP’s spam filters, your </text>
<text top="337" left="287" width="286" height="34" font="2">lecturers spam filters)</text>
<text top="399" left="246" width="953" height="34" font="2">There is a fuzzy line to deal with here – when does an unsolicited email </text>
<text top="435" left="246" width="193" height="34" font="2">cross the line?</text>
<text top="492" left="246" width="952" height="34" font="2">Internet Service Provider level filtering has reduced the issue by rapidly </text>
<text top="528" left="246" width="547" height="34" font="2">blocking people from sending information</text>
</page>
